WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.800
My name is Shannon Pileggi, and I am on the R-Ladies leadership team.

00:00:03.800 --> 00:00:07.040
I was not scheduled to give this presentation today,

00:00:07.040 --> 00:00:10.000
so Avery Giudici was scheduled to give this presentation,

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:13.760
and unfortunately, she could not attend last minute.

00:00:13.760 --> 00:00:15.680
What I'm going to be talking to you about today

00:00:15.680 --> 00:00:19.040
is how we operate as a global team,

00:00:19.040 --> 00:00:22.280
as a global organization in R-Ladies.

00:00:22.280 --> 00:00:25.320
I'm going to talk to you about how we think about infrastructure

00:00:25.320 --> 00:00:27.040
for that global organization,

00:00:27.040 --> 00:00:31.840
especially in the context of the diverse needs of our community.

00:00:31.840 --> 00:00:33.919
I'm going to start off by showing you a challenge

00:00:33.919 --> 00:00:36.639
that we face as an organization,

00:00:36.639 --> 00:00:38.240
kind of help you learn a little bit more

00:00:38.240 --> 00:00:40.720
about why that's a challenge for us

00:00:40.720 --> 00:00:44.720
and how we addressed it with new infrastructure.

00:00:44.720 --> 00:00:47.919
So here's the challenge that we faced.

00:00:47.919 --> 00:00:50.439
I saw this quote on social media.

00:00:50.439 --> 00:00:52.439
I was still trying to make up my mind

00:00:52.439 --> 00:00:55.720
on whether to get in touch with the R-Ladies community.

00:00:55.720 --> 00:00:58.720
If someone called me a lady, I would last,

00:00:58.720 --> 00:01:01.639
but it seems to be inclusive.

00:01:01.639 --> 00:01:03.919
To understand why this is a problem for us,

00:01:03.919 --> 00:01:07.400
you have to understand more about our community.

00:01:07.400 --> 00:01:10.320
So here we go.

00:01:10.320 --> 00:01:12.839
R-Ladies is a worldwide organization

00:01:12.839 --> 00:01:15.519
that promotes gender diversity in our community

00:01:15.519 --> 00:01:20.199
via meetups and mentorship in a friendly and safe environment.

00:01:20.199 --> 00:01:22.440
And I want to pause here and be explicit

00:01:22.440 --> 00:01:25.360
about what gender diversity means to us.

00:01:25.360 --> 00:01:28.080
Gender diversity is not just promoting the work

00:01:28.080 --> 00:01:32.000
of a cis woman like myself and a group of cis men.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:34.879
Gender diversity also includes individuals

00:01:34.879 --> 00:01:39.239
that are trans men, trans women, non-binary, and agender,

00:01:39.239 --> 00:01:41.360
and that is not an exhaustive list.

00:01:43.919 --> 00:01:47.199
We have over 200 R-Ladies chapters across the world.

00:01:47.199 --> 00:01:49.199
We are city-based chapters.

00:01:50.199 --> 00:01:54.480
And since the very first event was hosted in 2012,

00:01:54.480 --> 00:01:58.199
we've had over 4,000 R-Ladies events

00:01:58.199 --> 00:02:00.599
to create this community and promote our work.

00:02:04.199 --> 00:02:05.400
We have a leadership team.

00:02:05.400 --> 00:02:07.519
There's five of us.

00:02:07.519 --> 00:02:10.639
Riva from Chile, Avery from the United States,

00:02:10.639 --> 00:02:12.399
myself from the United States,

00:02:12.399 --> 00:02:17.679
Mo from Norway, and Johnny from Argentina.

00:02:18.679 --> 00:02:20.279
We call ourselves a leadership team,

00:02:20.279 --> 00:02:22.479
but we're really the people on the paperwork.

00:02:22.479 --> 00:02:23.639
We've signed the paperwork.

00:02:23.639 --> 00:02:25.080
We're on the board of directors

00:02:25.080 --> 00:02:28.960
for the actual nonprofit organization.

00:02:28.960 --> 00:02:32.000
We do things like strategic planning, finances,

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:35.320
fundraising, operational and infrastructure management,

00:02:35.320 --> 00:02:38.000
and reporting and documentation.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:39.600
Because, you know, I thought to myself,

00:02:39.600 --> 00:02:42.279
filing my own personal taxes is so much fun,

00:02:42.279 --> 00:02:44.559
I want to find a way to do it twice this year.

00:02:45.559 --> 00:02:47.759
Beyond that, the five of us consider ourselves

00:02:47.759 --> 00:02:50.960
part of a larger global team.

00:02:50.960 --> 00:02:53.960
The global team achieves a lot.

00:02:53.960 --> 00:02:57.360
We do website, code of conduct adherence,

00:02:57.360 --> 00:02:59.960
community Slack management, email management,

00:02:59.960 --> 00:03:02.559
abstract review system, onboarding of new chapters,

00:03:02.559 --> 00:03:04.960
chapter mentoring, directory management,

00:03:04.960 --> 00:03:08.160
Meetup Pro, blog, conferences, social media,

00:03:08.160 --> 00:03:09.960
campaigns, translation.

00:03:09.960 --> 00:03:12.960
Our contribution working group runs all of that.

00:03:12.960 --> 00:03:15.360
Our contribution working group runs grant administration

00:03:15.360 --> 00:03:18.160
and the R Consortium ISC board.

00:03:18.160 --> 00:03:21.559
We need a lot of people to support all of these activities,

00:03:21.559 --> 00:03:23.559
and we're so grateful for the global team.

00:03:26.559 --> 00:03:30.639
Beyond that, we have our city-based chapters

00:03:30.639 --> 00:03:32.559
that are led by chapter organizers

00:03:32.559 --> 00:03:35.360
who also pour an immense amount of time

00:03:35.360 --> 00:03:39.360
and energy into the organization by organizing meetups

00:03:39.360 --> 00:03:41.360
and by securing speakers,

00:03:41.360 --> 00:03:44.559
and by understanding what their local cities need

00:03:44.559 --> 00:03:46.759
in order to thrive.

00:03:46.759 --> 00:03:49.559
And then we have our community members

00:03:49.559 --> 00:03:51.559
who attend our chapter events,

00:03:51.559 --> 00:03:54.559
who also pour time and energy into the organization

00:03:54.559 --> 00:03:56.960
by attending events, by sharing their knowledge,

00:03:56.960 --> 00:04:00.559
by learning from others, and by becoming speakers.

00:04:03.759 --> 00:04:06.559
Managing all of this requires an enormous amount

00:04:06.559 --> 00:04:09.559
of infrastructure, or I should say supporting all of this.

00:04:11.559 --> 00:04:14.559
And we think about our infrastructure in two buckets.

00:04:14.559 --> 00:04:16.959
We have our technical infrastructure,

00:04:16.959 --> 00:04:20.959
which are our tools, our software, and our platforms.

00:04:20.959 --> 00:04:23.359
And we also have our social infrastructure,

00:04:23.359 --> 00:04:26.359
which is our guidelines and resources.

00:04:26.359 --> 00:04:28.559
Think about documentation

00:04:28.559 --> 00:04:30.559
that tells you how to get things done

00:04:30.559 --> 00:04:32.559
and who to ask for for help.

00:04:34.760 --> 00:04:36.760
Together, our technical infrastructure

00:04:36.760 --> 00:04:38.559
and our social infrastructure

00:04:38.559 --> 00:04:40.760
are what enable community participation

00:04:40.760 --> 00:04:44.559
and development of personal connections.

00:04:44.559 --> 00:04:47.160
Of course, none of the infrastructure matters

00:04:47.160 --> 00:04:48.959
if we don't have people.

00:04:48.959 --> 00:04:51.760
So how do we get people?

00:04:51.760 --> 00:04:53.760
There's a blog post from 2022

00:04:53.760 --> 00:04:57.559
that outlined pathways to inclusion in a community.

00:04:57.559 --> 00:04:59.760
We start off with awareness.

00:04:59.760 --> 00:05:01.959
I've heard of this thing.

00:05:01.959 --> 00:05:03.359
Understanding.

00:05:03.359 --> 00:05:06.959
I understand what this is about.

00:05:07.160 --> 00:05:08.559
Identification.

00:05:08.559 --> 00:05:11.359
I can see myself doing this.

00:05:11.359 --> 00:05:12.959
Access.

00:05:12.959 --> 00:05:17.160
I can physically, logistically, and financially do this.

00:05:17.160 --> 00:05:18.559
Belonging.

00:05:18.559 --> 00:05:20.959
I feel like I fit in here.

00:05:20.959 --> 00:05:22.359
And ownership.

00:05:22.359 --> 00:05:25.959
I care enough to take responsibility for this.

00:05:25.959 --> 00:05:27.959
I can tell you for me personally,

00:05:27.959 --> 00:05:31.359
it took me about seven years to go on this pathway.

00:05:32.359 --> 00:05:34.959
We can also think about how our infrastructure

00:05:34.959 --> 00:05:37.359
supports this pathway to inclusion.

00:05:37.359 --> 00:05:39.959
So, for example, on the technical side,

00:05:39.959 --> 00:05:41.359
we have our social media.

00:05:41.359 --> 00:05:42.559
We have website.

00:05:42.559 --> 00:05:43.959
We have community Slack.

00:05:43.959 --> 00:05:44.959
We have Zoom.

00:05:44.959 --> 00:05:45.959
We have a directory.

00:05:45.959 --> 00:05:48.559
We have one password.

00:05:48.559 --> 00:05:50.760
Then we also have our guidelines and resources

00:05:50.760 --> 00:05:53.559
on the social infrastructure side.

00:05:53.559 --> 00:05:56.160
We have our branding, our mission statement,

00:05:56.160 --> 00:05:58.359
our code of conduct, the rules,

00:05:58.959 --> 00:06:01.559
And if you have your own community

00:06:01.559 --> 00:06:04.160
and you're not really sure where to start,

00:06:04.160 --> 00:06:06.160
I would encourage you to start here

00:06:06.160 --> 00:06:09.160
with your mission statement and your code of conduct.

00:06:09.160 --> 00:06:11.559
These are things that are really going to help individuals

00:06:11.559 --> 00:06:13.959
understand what your community is about,

00:06:13.959 --> 00:06:15.760
what you're aiming to achieve,

00:06:15.760 --> 00:06:18.559
and how they're going to do that in a safe way.

00:06:18.559 --> 00:06:20.760
So, for example, if you're a young person,

00:06:20.760 --> 00:06:23.359
you're going to want to know what your goals are.

00:06:23.359 --> 00:06:25.760
You're going to want to know what your goals are.

00:06:25.760 --> 00:06:28.160
You're going to want to know what your goals are.

00:06:28.359 --> 00:06:30.760
You're going to want to know what your goals are.

00:06:30.760 --> 00:06:33.359
And you're going to want to know what your goals are.

00:06:33.359 --> 00:06:34.760
So, in a lot of ways,

00:06:34.760 --> 00:06:37.959
this is a very safe way.

00:06:37.959 --> 00:06:40.559
And I also encourage you to think about your community

00:06:40.559 --> 00:06:41.959
very broadly.

00:06:41.959 --> 00:06:45.359
For example, I would consider a group of open source

00:06:45.359 --> 00:06:47.760
package developers a community

00:06:47.760 --> 00:06:49.959
that requires social infrastructure

00:06:49.959 --> 00:06:51.959
that tells people how to onboard

00:06:51.959 --> 00:06:55.559
and how to participate when they want to contribute code.

00:06:55.559 --> 00:06:57.359
They might not need a mission statement

00:06:57.559 --> 00:06:59.160
or a mission statement.

00:06:59.160 --> 00:07:00.959
They might need a mission statement

00:07:00.959 --> 00:07:02.760
or a mission statement.

00:07:02.760 --> 00:07:04.559
They might need a mission statement

00:07:04.559 --> 00:07:06.359
or a mission statement.

00:07:06.359 --> 00:07:08.559
And so, I would consider a group of open source

00:07:08.559 --> 00:07:10.559
package developers

00:07:10.559 --> 00:07:13.359
a community that requires social infrastructure

00:07:13.359 --> 00:07:15.559
that tells people how to onboard

00:07:15.559 --> 00:07:18.959
and how to participate when they want to contribute code.

00:07:18.959 --> 00:07:22.160
Beyond this, we have different people in our organization

00:07:22.160 --> 00:07:24.559
that just have different needs.

00:07:25.160 --> 00:07:27.959
Chapter organizers, global team, leadership team.

00:07:27.959 --> 00:07:30.160
And we have different questions we need answered,

00:07:30.160 --> 00:07:32.160
like how to actually get things done

00:07:32.160 --> 00:07:34.760
and how to organize events.

00:07:34.760 --> 00:07:37.359
So, for them, we have our organizer slack

00:07:37.359 --> 00:07:38.760
and our internal guide,

00:07:38.760 --> 00:07:42.959
which is also public-facing.

00:07:42.959 --> 00:07:44.359
And to be clear,

00:07:44.359 --> 00:07:46.760
all of this comes back down to the global team,

00:07:46.760 --> 00:07:51.760
which develop and maintain that centralized infrastructure.

00:07:55.559 --> 00:07:59.559
And even though we have this centralized infrastructure,

00:07:59.559 --> 00:08:02.559
we are part of a global organization

00:08:02.559 --> 00:08:04.959
and needs across the world vary.

00:08:04.959 --> 00:08:07.160
So, as Nadeja Serow said,

00:08:07.160 --> 00:08:10.559
I believe best practices depend on how the chapter organizers

00:08:10.559 --> 00:08:15.559
can adapt to the reality to make people comfortable

00:08:15.559 --> 00:08:20.559
at coming to the meetups and also being speakers.

00:08:21.559 --> 00:08:22.959
So, what does this look like for us?

00:08:22.959 --> 00:08:26.760
Let's take a look at four chapters across the world.

00:08:26.760 --> 00:08:30.359
Gaviron in Botswana, Sao Paolo in Brazil,

00:08:30.359 --> 00:08:32.760
Vienna in Austria, where USAR was just held,

00:08:32.760 --> 00:08:36.159
and Seattle, where we are right now.

00:08:36.159 --> 00:08:39.359
These four chapters have different technical infrastructure

00:08:39.359 --> 00:08:42.359
for communicating with their community members.

00:08:42.359 --> 00:08:43.559
So, for example,

00:08:43.559 --> 00:08:45.559
we have a group of community members

00:08:45.559 --> 00:08:47.559
that are working on a project

00:08:48.559 --> 00:08:51.359
for communicating with their community members.

00:08:51.359 --> 00:08:56.159
They use WhatsApp, Telegram, Meetup, or Slack.

00:08:56.159 --> 00:08:58.359
And they also have different social infrastructure.

00:08:58.359 --> 00:09:00.760
Their guidelines and resources might vary,

00:09:00.760 --> 00:09:02.960
and they're also in different languages,

00:09:02.960 --> 00:09:07.760
like English or Portuguese or other native languages.

00:09:07.760 --> 00:09:11.760
And we trust our local community chapters

00:09:11.760 --> 00:09:14.960
to determine what is best for their community.

00:09:14.960 --> 00:09:18.559
They're going to vary in other meaningful ways as well.

00:09:18.559 --> 00:09:21.559
They're going to vary on the day of the week that they meet,

00:09:21.559 --> 00:09:23.159
the time of the day,

00:09:23.159 --> 00:09:25.960
and the support that they are able to give to their community

00:09:25.960 --> 00:09:27.760
or what their community needs.

00:09:27.760 --> 00:09:31.359
For example, some might provide free transportation to events

00:09:31.359 --> 00:09:33.359
or child care on site.

00:09:36.760 --> 00:09:44.159
And to be clear, nonprofit is not the same as free.

00:09:44.159 --> 00:09:47.960
I cannot estimate the number of volunteer hours

00:09:47.960 --> 00:09:50.159
that have gone into this organization

00:09:50.159 --> 00:09:53.159
since 2012 to make this run.

00:09:53.159 --> 00:09:56.359
We have no paid staff.

00:09:56.359 --> 00:09:59.159
We are doing this all on our own time.

00:10:01.559 --> 00:10:04.760
And then there's actually, like, a real cost.

00:10:04.760 --> 00:10:06.760
So our annual operating costs

00:10:06.760 --> 00:10:13.159
for the global infrastructure is $50,000 U.S.

00:10:13.359 --> 00:10:15.359
And we're so grateful that this is funded

00:10:15.359 --> 00:10:18.760
by the R Consortium and individual donations.

00:10:23.359 --> 00:10:24.960
So let's go back to that example,

00:10:24.960 --> 00:10:26.960
the challenge that we face.

00:10:29.960 --> 00:10:31.760
I'm still trying to make up my mind

00:10:31.760 --> 00:10:35.159
on whether to get in touch with the R Ladies community.

00:10:35.159 --> 00:10:37.559
If someone called me a lady, I would lash,

00:10:37.559 --> 00:10:40.960
but it seems to be inclusive.

00:10:40.960 --> 00:10:45.359
This is from a person who on social media is openly trans.

00:10:47.559 --> 00:10:49.559
And this is a problem for us

00:10:49.559 --> 00:10:53.159
because this person has hit that first rung

00:10:53.159 --> 00:10:54.960
to their pathway to inclusion.

00:10:54.960 --> 00:10:57.960
They know we exist,

00:10:57.960 --> 00:11:01.559
but they don't know if they belong with us.

00:11:01.559 --> 00:11:03.559
And that's a problem.

00:11:06.559 --> 00:11:09.559
So we created a new process

00:11:09.559 --> 00:11:14.159
and some new infrastructure in order to address this challenge.

00:11:14.159 --> 00:11:15.760
In April of this year,

00:11:15.760 --> 00:11:18.960
we opened an issue on our community repository

00:11:18.960 --> 00:11:22.159
in our R Ladies GitHub organization.

00:11:22.159 --> 00:11:23.559
The title of this issue is

00:11:23.559 --> 00:11:27.760
Rebranding from R Ladies to R Ladies Past.

00:11:27.760 --> 00:11:30.359
We talk about the mission of our organization

00:11:30.359 --> 00:11:34.359
and how our name doesn't necessarily support our mission.

00:11:34.359 --> 00:11:37.760
We've gotten feedback about this over the years.

00:11:37.760 --> 00:11:41.159
We invite people to comment on this issue.

00:11:41.159 --> 00:11:43.559
Talk to us about what you think.

00:11:43.559 --> 00:11:46.159
Do you think it's a good idea to stay R Ladies?

00:11:46.159 --> 00:11:48.559
Should we become R Ladies Plus?

00:11:48.559 --> 00:11:50.760
Should we become some name entirely different

00:11:50.760 --> 00:11:53.960
that we haven't thought of?

00:11:53.960 --> 00:11:55.760
We talk about the pros of this.

00:11:55.760 --> 00:11:59.159
This change could be meaningful for members of our community

00:11:59.159 --> 00:12:01.960
to identify with what we do better.

00:12:01.960 --> 00:12:03.760
We talk about the cons of this.

00:12:03.760 --> 00:12:06.359
We have really large brand name recognition

00:12:06.559 --> 00:12:09.159
and it could be hard to shift that.

00:12:09.159 --> 00:12:11.359
And there's other cons as well.

00:12:11.359 --> 00:12:14.559
Because remember, we are a global organization

00:12:14.559 --> 00:12:18.559
and we have to respect the needs of our local communities.

00:12:18.559 --> 00:12:23.359
And in some countries, being a minority gender is deemed illegal.

00:12:23.359 --> 00:12:25.760
Which means that in those countries,

00:12:25.760 --> 00:12:29.359
hosting an event branded as R Ladies Plus

00:12:29.359 --> 00:12:31.760
could pose a risk to event organizers

00:12:31.760 --> 00:12:34.760
and attendees for persecution.

00:12:36.960 --> 00:12:40.559
So we created the best social infrastructure that we could.

00:12:40.559 --> 00:12:41.960
There's always room for improvement.

00:12:41.960 --> 00:12:47.159
But what we did is we had a very long and detailed readme

00:12:47.159 --> 00:12:50.960
about how this community discussion would operate.

00:12:50.960 --> 00:12:52.960
We talked about the timeline.

00:12:52.960 --> 00:12:56.159
We talked about the ways you could contribute comments

00:12:56.159 --> 00:12:59.760
either by commenting on the GitHub discussion forum

00:12:59.760 --> 00:13:03.960
or by submitting an anonymous comment via a form.

00:13:04.159 --> 00:13:06.359
We talked about the expectations in terms of

00:13:06.359 --> 00:13:10.760
please contribute your discussion in English as a common language.

00:13:10.760 --> 00:13:13.359
And we also talked about how we were going to have moderators

00:13:13.359 --> 00:13:17.359
for this discussion to ensure that the code of conduct was followed.

00:13:19.960 --> 00:13:22.359
And then of course, we had our technical infrastructure

00:13:22.359 --> 00:13:23.960
to make this happen.

00:13:23.960 --> 00:13:26.760
We used GitHub as a platform for discussion.

00:13:26.760 --> 00:13:30.960
We used Airtable to collect the form responses.

00:13:31.960 --> 00:13:35.760
And then we used Slack as a tool to communicate about that

00:13:35.760 --> 00:13:37.760
or be notified.

00:13:37.760 --> 00:13:40.159
We had a really nice Airtable automation

00:13:40.159 --> 00:13:41.960
so that when a new form was submitted,

00:13:41.960 --> 00:13:45.359
it sent a message directly to Slack that looked like this.

00:13:45.359 --> 00:13:47.960
A new anonymous comment has been submitted.

00:13:47.960 --> 00:13:51.960
And that way we knew automatically to review it

00:13:51.960 --> 00:13:54.960
for posting on the forum.

00:13:57.760 --> 00:13:59.760
And I'm not here today to tell you

00:13:59.760 --> 00:14:02.159
the result of the decision.

00:14:02.159 --> 00:14:04.559
The rebranding decision is in progress.

00:14:04.559 --> 00:14:06.760
And you're welcome to go look at all of the thoughts

00:14:06.760 --> 00:14:08.760
that were contributed.

00:14:08.760 --> 00:14:11.960
We are so grateful that the community came in

00:14:11.960 --> 00:14:13.760
and talked about this with us

00:14:13.760 --> 00:14:16.559
because we did not feel capable of a leadership team

00:14:16.559 --> 00:14:18.159
of seeing all the points of view

00:14:18.159 --> 00:14:20.960
in our narrow limited worldview.

00:14:20.960 --> 00:14:24.559
And we learned so much from this discussion

00:14:24.559 --> 00:14:29.559
that even among cis women, people don't like the word ladies.

00:14:29.760 --> 00:14:35.559
And either for personal reasons or like bigger reasons

00:14:35.559 --> 00:14:41.559
that it imposes feelings and sentiments of colonization.

00:14:41.559 --> 00:14:45.960
And people supplied so many different great ideas

00:14:45.960 --> 00:14:48.960
in terms of why we should be stay our ladies,

00:14:48.960 --> 00:14:54.359
move to our ladies plus, or be some other name entirely.

00:14:54.359 --> 00:14:57.760
And again, going back to a global organization,

00:14:57.760 --> 00:15:02.159
it's really important to us that whatever name we have

00:15:02.159 --> 00:15:05.159
resonates with people across the world.

00:15:05.159 --> 00:15:07.559
If your native language is not English,

00:15:07.559 --> 00:15:13.559
whatever name we have has to be readily understood to you.

00:15:14.960 --> 00:15:16.760
But we learned something even more important

00:15:16.760 --> 00:15:19.159
through this process.

00:15:19.159 --> 00:15:21.559
We learned that regardless of the outcome,

00:15:21.559 --> 00:15:24.559
we need better social infrastructure

00:15:24.559 --> 00:15:27.159
to facilitate the pathways to inclusion

00:15:27.159 --> 00:15:30.159
for gender diverse members of our community.

00:15:30.159 --> 00:15:33.159
There's a lot more that we could be doing.

00:15:34.960 --> 00:15:38.559
So thoughts for your community.

00:15:38.559 --> 00:15:40.159
Thriving communities require

00:15:40.159 --> 00:15:44.159
both technical and social infrastructure.

00:15:45.960 --> 00:15:51.559
That technical infrastructure, almost the easy part,

00:15:51.559 --> 00:15:54.159
it satisfies your operational needs

00:15:54.159 --> 00:15:58.359
and we're here because we like doing tech things.

00:15:58.359 --> 00:16:01.559
The social infrastructure, I would argue, is the hard part,

00:16:01.559 --> 00:16:05.159
writing down that documentation and getting it right.

00:16:05.159 --> 00:16:07.960
And the social infrastructure, I would also argue,

00:16:07.960 --> 00:16:10.559
is the most important part

00:16:10.559 --> 00:16:12.359
because it's going to nourish the growth

00:16:12.359 --> 00:16:14.159
and longevity of that community.

00:16:14.159 --> 00:16:15.760
It's going to be what sustains it,

00:16:15.760 --> 00:16:18.760
where that tech stack can change over time.

00:16:19.760 --> 00:16:22.559
And in a global community

00:16:22.559 --> 00:16:25.359
or in any diverse community that you have,

00:16:25.359 --> 00:16:28.159
balancing that standardization and flexibility

00:16:28.159 --> 00:16:31.359
is going to foster community success.

00:16:31.359 --> 00:16:33.359
Thank you.

00:16:33.359 --> 00:16:35.960
Thank you.

